The paper deals with the development of adaptive attacker strategies against moving target cyber defenses, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The use of finite state machine (FSM) constructs and evolutionary algorithms to model attacker response strategies suggests the involvement of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The study of defender scheduling policies and their impact on attacker strategies involves software engineering (cs.SE) and game theory (cs.GT) sub-categories.
